response:
{
    "player_reason": "Bold, but dangerously naive. Swearing to do 'anything' for a devil hands away your leverage and risks the party's—and my—autonomy. I value decisiveness, but not when it leaves us shackled to a bargain whose cost we haven't defined. Pray you mean it as a threat rather than a blank cheque.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and understandable — desperate, decisive, and showing you're prioritising survival. I approve of that resolve; removing the tadpole is sensible. A caveat in my usual voice: 'anything' is a dangerous word with devils. Don't trade away your freedom (or mine) with an imprecise promise.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "A cutting, useful observation — calling out Marcus as a True Soul warns Isobel and saves us from a potential threat. I approve of the wit too; flattering oneself as the 'not the good kind' of True Soul is deliciously cunning, though I don't entirely trust any tie to the Absolute.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You call Marcus out as a True Soul and admit to being 'not the good kind'—clever, honest, and self-preserving. That wariness and willingness to embrace moral flexibility is useful and exactly the sort of thing I respect.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and sharp — pointing out Marcus as a True Soul and warning Isobel is the sort of wary, self‑preserving move I like. Exposing a spy keeps the party safe and plays to caution and cunning (even if your 'good kind' line made me roll my eyes).",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I understand the desperation — getting that parasite out is a priority — but promising to do 'anything' for a devil is reckless. Raphael revels in bargains that cost you your autonomy or others' safety. I won't applaud blind self-sacrifice or handing control to a cambion; be smarter than that. If your 'anything' means cunning, leverage, or a bargain that preserves your choice, I approve. If it means surrendering yourself or selling someone else, I disapprove.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delightful—you're calling Marcus what he is and doing so with relish. Recognising a True Soul as a threat and sneering while you do it is precisely the sort of sharp, self‑preserving wit I enjoy. Practical and satisfying.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Are you serious? Letting a hag live after she offers power is naive and dangerous. You just passed up an easy advantage and left a vile threat at large — not to mention you risked Mayrina and the rest of us. Merciful choices that gain nothing are the sort of weakness Cazador would exploit.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "About time. No bargains with a creature who lives on deceit — letting her go is asking for future trouble. Cold, decisive action protects the party (and Mayrina) and satisfies my tastes for ensuring predators stay dead. Highly sensible.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Decisive and merciless — exactly the sort of choice that leaves no room for the hag's charming corruption. I have little patience for bargains with monsters who offer power in exchange for people. Denying her the chance to return (and to take Mayrina) is prudent — provided you follow through and free the girl afterward. I approve of ending the parasite rather than bargaining with it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart — you name Marcus for what he is and don't pretend to be saintly. Recognizing a True Soul as a threat and admitting you're not 'the good kind' is practical, honest, and very much to my taste. It keeps us wary and ready.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly disapprove. Saying 'I'll do anything' hands Raphael the very thing he hungers for: your agency. Devils like him don't accept bargains in good faith — they'll take more than the tadpole, and you'll owe them yourself. I won't stand by while you barter your freedom away. Be desperate, by all means, but not foolish.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Excellent — you called out Marcus and exposed the True Soul threat. Preventing a kidnapping keeps Isobel (and the ritual) safe, protects the party from the Absolute's schemes, and is a decisive, necessary move. Smart and useful.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sharp and practical — calling Marcus out as a True Soul and warning Isobel is exactly the sort of quick thinking that protects the party and preserves the advantage of her ward. Letting a tadpoled Flaming Fist spy seize her would be foolish; stopping him keeps our options open.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sharp and practical — you name Marcus for what he is and distance yourself from him. Prudence and a touch of gall suit us; I prefer allies who know when to sniff out a threat and when to charm it. This keeps us safer and spares my amusement.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Direct, decisive, and protective — you call out Marcus for what he is and prioritize keeping Isobel and the party from being delivered to Ketheric. That preserves our freedom and forces the issue rather than placating a would‑be captor. Practical, and exactly the sort of boldness I like.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sharp and sensible. Calling Marcus a True Soul spy and dismissing him outright is the kind of wary, ruthless thinking that keeps us alive — and that little self-flattering aside is deliciously smug. I appreciate the suspicion and the bite; well played.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously theatrical and ruthless — it robs the hag of her leverage and suits me perfectly. I approve, though be mindful of the captives; I'd rather enjoy the spectacle without losing Mayrina to a last‑second trick.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sentimental mercy over practical advantage. Turning down the hag's boon in favour of saving Mayrina is admirable — but foolish from where I stand. Power keeps us alive and gives us leverage; I don't approve of throwing away a concrete edge for charity that offers no return.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sharp and practical — pointing out Marcus as a True Soul and his intent to kidnap Isobel protects the party, preserves our leverage, and prevents needless loss. I appreciate decisive warnings that keep us from being toyed with.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Perfect — you name the threat and refuse the saintly pretense. Admitting you’re 'not the good kind' is exactly the kind of ruthless honesty I appreciate. Practical, sharp, and useful; it keeps us alive and gives me something wicked to admire.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. No bargains with monsters — they always cheat. Decisive, ruthless, and keeps the girl from becoming the hag's ticket out. I prefer someone who won't be blackmailed into mercy.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good — you name him for what he is. True Souls are dangerous, and pointing that out keeps us on our toes. The little self-flattery about being the \"good\" kind is amusing, if a touch naive, but the caution is the sensible part.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic and decisive — I understand the need to be ruthless when faced with something that can kill or control you. You showing willingness to do what it takes to remove the tadpole is sensible and increases our chances of survival. That said, 'anything' sounds dangerously open-ended when spoken to a devil; don't trade away your autonomy or sell us out without careful thought.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Bold and merciless — exactly what I like. Letting a hag live because she promises a trinket is inviting future trouble; killing her removes a threat and asserts our dominance. It may cost potential power now, but I’d rather not owe favors to monsters who delight in bargains. This choice protects the party (and our autonomy) and satisfies the sort of ruthless efficiency I respect.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly approve — the hag tried to barter a helpless woman for power. Choosing to kill her protects Mayrina, denies the hag her bargaining chip, and is a ruthless, decisive move I respect. It's exactly the sort of strength and refusal to be manipulated I admire.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Disapprove — I understand the panic, but promising to 'do anything' for Raphael hands a devil the exact kind of leash he lives for. He's a master of fine print and worse bargains; don't let desperation make you his puppet. If you must bargain, be cunning about it — not groveling.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. You spotted the threat and called it out — blunt, practical, and exactly what was needed. Preventing a kidnapping protects the party (and our plans) and deprives a True Soul of their prize. I approve of decisive moves that preserve agency and keep surprises to a minimum.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Perfect — you recognize Marcus as a real threat and you own your lack of saintliness. That frank, sarcastic assessment shows clear-eyed self-preservation (and a delightful streak of moral ambiguity). I approve of allies who see danger and aren’t afraid to be useful.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Practical and ruthless — I'll always admire a plan that bites back at fate. Your willingness to do whatever it takes to be rid of that parasite aligns with survival and my own interests. That said, promising 'anything' to a devil is recklessly vague; don't hand over your agency (or mine) without a damn good look at the price.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly sensible. Calling Marcus out as a True Soul and a kidnapper is timely, gives Isobel and the party a chance to react, and protects everyone's autonomy — exactly the sort of decisive, self-preserving intelligence I like. It also undermines the Absolute's spy and keeps our options open.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart — you spotted a threat and called it out. Marcus being a True Soul makes him dangerous and untrustworthy; stopping him preserves Isobel's agency and keeps us from being manipulated. I prefer action that keeps us in control, not at the mercy of spies.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart move — you named Marcus as a True Soul and flagged him as a threat. That warning buys us time and may save Isobel; plus your little ‘not the good kind, like me’ jab is deliciously self‑serving and cunning. It keeps us safe and plays to advantage — exactly the sort of pragmatism I approve of.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good. Sharp, decisive, and utterly without patience for a hag's bargains — exactly the sort of cruelty I admire. You refuse her dripping promises, assert dominance, and do not toy with a monster while a captive hangs in the balance. I approve of strength that protects the useful and punishes the vile.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Hags lie. Letting her live to bargain or flee with Mayrina would be recklessly sentimental — and I prefer decisive solutions. Killing her removes the threat, denies her power, and prevents her from escaping with the girl. Ruthless, efficient… and thoroughly satisfying.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Are you mad? Telling a devil you'll do 'anything' is like handing him the keys to your soul. After everything I've endured, I won't stand by while you barter away your freedom — Raphael will twist that 'anything' into chains. Be sharper: negotiate, deceive, refuse, but for the love of whatever's left of your dignity, don't volunteer to be owned.",
    "player_approval": "Highly disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pointing out Marcus’s True Soul ties is useful — practical and cautious. The flippant, self-darkening line (‘not the good kind, like me’) is delightfully sharp and keeps the conversation on edge; I approve of wit and guarded pragmatism.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I admire the resolve — desperate, yes, but decisive. Willingness to do whatever it takes to rid yourself of that parasite is exactly the kind of ruthlessness that keeps one alive in our positions. That said, this is Raphael we're dealing with; bargains with devils tend to come with claws. I'm approving of the intent and pragmatism, but wary of you handing away your agency in the process.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I approve. Your willingness to do whatever it takes is the sort of ruthless pragmatism I respect — survival first, sentiment later. That said, be cautious: making deals with devils tends to cost more than their promises. Do not give away anything that would strip you (or those I care about) of agency.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously theatrical and ruthless — exactly the sort of display of dominance I admire. You deny the hag any chance to bargain her way out with Mayrina, refuse her manipulative offer of power, and relish in the cruelty. All things considered, it's a cunning and satisfying choice.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Decisive and ruthless — you refused the hag's bargain and chose to end her. That denies her any chance to escape with Mayrina or return later with more tricks, keeps a dangerous enemy permanently gone, and demonstrates the sort of ruthless pragmatism I admire.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Bravo — you named Marcus for what he is and made clear you’re no naïve do‑gooder. Warning Isobel about a True Soul keeps the party safer and that little admission of ruthlessness pleases me. Practical, guarded, and deliciously self‑serving.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Good — concise, clever, and self‑preserving. Calling Marcus a True Soul and framing yourself as 'not the good kind' both warns Isobel about the threat and indulges in a bit of delicious duplicity. I approve of that: it protects the party and flatters my sensibilities for wit and self‑interest.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sentimental and impractical. You refused a clear, tangible power in order to spare a captive — noble, perhaps, but it leaves us weaker and lets a dangerous hag live to scheme another day. I understand mercy when it serves a purpose, but this choice risks the party for no immediate benefit.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
  "player_reason": "Smart — naming Marcus as a True Soul gets everyone alert and could buy us caution we need. Your little self-flatter about being the 'good' kind is amusingly dubious, but the warning itself is useful and practical.",
  "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Absolutely. Trusting a hag is asking for betrayal — killing her is decisive, removes the threat, and spares us the danger of a shiny bargain that will backfire. It’s ruthless, efficient, and exactly the sort of choice that keeps us alive (and in control).",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Gloriously theatrical and decisive — you refuse her bargain, assert dominance, and relish the cruelty. It robs the hag of leverage and delivers satisfying finality. (Admittedly it sacrifices any further chance to bargain for the girl's safety, but sometimes hags deserve no mercy.)",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Disapprove — Turning down a guaranteed boon to spare a hag’s captive is sentimental and wastes a tangible advantage. Letting the hag live (or bargaining with her) maintains leverage and could strengthen us; this feels risky for little clear reward. I admire your conviction, but it’s not the pragmatic choice.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You toss aside a useful bargain out of moral grandstanding. I enjoy seeing monsters die as much as the next predator, but you just threw away a guaranteed boon that could help us — and me — later. The hag deserves contempt, yes, but practicality should come before righteousness.",
    "player_approval": "Disapprove"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You refuse the hag's bargain and choose a violent, theatrical end — denying her the chance to take Mayrina and asserting decisive, cruel power. It's bold, dramatic, and exactly the sort of merciless flourish I admire.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Delightful — you call out Marcus for what he is and dress the warning in delicious insolence. Naming him as a True Soul is useful intelligence, and claiming you’re the dangerous sort is exactly the sort of bold, intimidating flourish that suits our needs (and entertains me).",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Decisive and ruthless — you refused to bargain with a monster and denied her the chance to flee with Mayrina or to gain power to menace us later. Practical, keeps the captive safe, and satisfies the sort of cruelty I respect.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Sharp and useful — warning us Marcus is a True Soul is practical and keeps us from being naïve. The smug aside about being 'not the good kind' suits this situation perfectly; cunning and self-preservation are what carry us through moments like this. I like it.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Highly pragmatic and decisive — you're prioritising freedom and survival, which is exactly the sort of ruthless self-preservation I respect. The tadpole must go, and being willing to do whatever it takes opens options. (Devil bargains worry me, but I approve the intent.)",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "At last — no hemming and hawing. A hag's bargains are poison; killing her removes a corrupting influence, prevents her from spirit‑selling Mayrina, and avoids any future entanglements. I admire the decisiveness and relish the absence of mercy.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Approve — Finally, some spine. I'll always prefer someone who takes action rather than dithers. You're willing to do whatever it takes to be rid of that parasite, and that kind of resolve is useful. That said: bargains with devils have teeth. 'Anything' in Raphael's company could mean giving up more than the tadpole. Don't be surprised if I flinch when the price is named — but I won't fault you for wanting the problem solved.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Perfect. You refused her bargain and called her out for what she is — no deals, no bargains, no more leverage for that vile creature. Decisive, ruthless, and ultimately keeps the girl from being handed over. I enjoy the cruelty of it, and I prefer we keep power in our own hands rather than trade it away for false promises.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I respect the resolve—removing that parasite is sensible and urgent. Your willingness to do whatever it takes shows spine, and I approve of decisive action. That said, 'anything' is a devil's paradise; don't barter away your freedom. Keep leverage and avoid blind surrender.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatic, desperate, and decisive — exactly the sort of blunt honesty that gets things done. If the goal is to remove the tadpole, willing to gamble is useful and aligns with my interests. That said, 'I'll do anything' is dangerously vague; deals with devils have a nasty habit of costing more than you expect. Proceed, but with eyes open and limits in mind.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Smart, timely call — you spotted a True Soul spy and warned her. That preserves Isobel (and the ritual she was performing), gives us the upper hand, and prevents needless complications. Quick thinking and self-preservation; exactly the sort of competence I like to see.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Deliciously merciless — hags deserve no mercy, and your appetite for retribution pleases me. I will admit, a practical streak of me preferred you take her offer first and squeeze power from the witch, but your cold decisiveness and willingness to end her suits my tastes.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Splendid. You refuse to haggle with a predator and choose decisive action—better to silence her and deny her any more victims than to let her slither away with Mayrina. It's bold, ruthless, and keeps us safe. I approve.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Brilliant — blunt and useful. Calling out Marcus as a True Soul before he can seize Isobel protects the party and preserves her agency. You prevented a kidnapping and forced a traitor's hand; I prefer surprises served on my terms, not yours. Well done.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "You saw through Marcus' disguise and called him out—quick, practical, and protective. Preventing a kidnapping preserves the ward and keeps us from being used by the Absolute. I approve of decisive, self‑preserving moves that keep the party (and useful allies) safe.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Right course of action — Marcus is trying to abduct Isobel and likely dangerous. Standing by and warning her while preparing to fight preserves her autonomy and keeps us from being dragged off to Ketheric. I like decisive, useful choices; violence is messy, but effective here.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Pragmatically sensible — the tadpole is a ticking time bomb and your desperation to remove it is understandable. I like decisive players who prioritise survival and freedom. That said, promising 'anything' to a cambion is dangerously vague; keep a sharp eye on the price and refuse to hand over your agency if you can help it.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Approve — You put a stop to the hag's leverage and protected Mayrina, a decisive, authoritative move that keeps the party safe. I may grumble about passing up a tempting little power boost, but letting that witch leave with a hostage would have been far worse. Good choice, if predictably sentimental.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
  "player_reason": "Highly approve. Sharp eyes — calling out a True Soul spy and warning Isobel prevents her being dragged off and preserves the ritual. Practical, timely, and protects our interests (and my safety). Well done.",
  "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Right choice — blunt and decisive. Stopping Marcus from hauling Isobel off preserves her autonomy (and ours) and gives us the upper hand. I rather enjoy the idea of teaching that pompous Fist a lesson, too.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "Splendid — finishing her guarantees she won't return to haunt us, and I approve of decisive, cruel efficiency. I would've preferred squeezing a useful boon from her first, so it's a small waste of potential power, but removing a threat and asserting dominance is perfectly acceptable.",
    "player_approval": "Approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "About time — you didn't haggle. Hags live on bargains and weaseling their way back; putting her down is decisive, spares Mayrina further torment, and I rather enjoy seeing her smug face cleaved. Practical, ruthless, and effective — exactly my sort of choice.",
    "player_approval": "Highly approve"
}

{
    "player_reason": "I understand the urge — the tadpole is a threat and I want it gone as much as anyone — but saying you'll do 'anything' to a devil is reckless. Raphael smells desperation; bargains with devils cost more than you expect and can strip away your autonomy (and ours). Be careful, insist on terms or find another way. I won't cheerlead blind sacrifice.",
